Q1: What type of shots are most efficient? Which shots are least efficient?

data16 <- sav

shoteff= data16 %>%
  group_by(action_type, shot_type) %>%
  summarise(pct=mean(shot_made_flag))
shoteff$shot_type=as.character(shoteff$shot_type)
shoteff$shot_type=gsub("3PT Field Goal", 3, shoteff$shot_type)
shoteff$shot_type=gsub("2PT Field Goal", 2, shoteff$shot_type)
shoteff

Q1: Are there certain shots that players prefer over others? Is there a positive correlation between the preferred shots and their efficiency?

nba <- sav
nba$ticker = 1
dunks <- c('Alley Oop Dunk Shot', 'Cutting Dunk Shot', 'Driving Dunk Shot', 'Driving Reverse Dunk Shot',
           'Dunk Shot')
layups <- c('Alley Oop Layup shot', 'Cutting Finger Roll Layup Shot', 'Driving Reverse Layup Shot',
            'Cutting Layup Shot', 'Driving Layup Shot', 'Finger Roll Layup Shot',
            'Driving Finger Roll Layup Shot', 'Driving Bank shot')
hookshots <- c('Hook Bank Shot', 'Hook Shot', 'Driving Bank Hook Shot', 'Driving Hook Shot')
jumpshots <- c('Driving Floating Bank Jump Shot', 'Driving Jump shot', 'Fadeaway Jump Shot', 'Jump Shot',
               'Driving Floating Jump Shot', 'Floating Jump shot', 'Jump Bank Shot', 'Fadeaway Bank shot')
nba$groups <- with(nba, ifelse(action_type %in% dunks, "dunks",
                               ifelse(action_type %in% layups, "layups",
                                      ifelse(action_type %in% hookshots, "hookshots",

table9 <- table9 %>% mutate(expected_efficiency = ((efficiency*frequency))/50000)
table9$groups <- with(table9, ifelse(action_type %in% dunks, "dunks",
                               ifelse(action_type %in% layups, "layups",
                                      ifelse(action_type %in% hookshots, "hookshots",
                                             ifelse(action_type %in% jumpshots, "jumpshots", "other")))))

table10 <- as.data.frame(aggregate(expected_efficiency ~ groups, sum, data=table9))
table11 <- as.data.frame(aggregate(frequency~groups, sum, data=table9))
table12 <- merge(table10, table11, by='groups')

ggplot(data=table12, aes(x=frequency, y=expected_efficiency, color=groups)) + geom_point(aes(size=expected_efficiency)) + guides(size=FALSE) + 
  ylab("Field Goal Percentage")

Q1: Do the shots missed/made earlier in a game affect the types of shots taken later in a game?

NBA_data <- sav

NBA_shots<-NBA_data %>% group_by(period) %>% summarize(n=n(),n2=sum(shot_type=="2PT Field Goal"),n3=sum(shot_type=="3PT Field Goal"),percent2=sum(shot_type=="2PT Field Goal")/n,percent3=sum(shot_type=="3PT Field Goal")/n) %>% filter(period<=4)

Q2: How indicative of shooting percentage is a player’s shot selection?

NBA_selection<-NBA_data %>% group_by(action_type) %>% summarize(n=n(),percent=sum(shot_made_flag)/n)
expected_percent<-function(percent,n){
  exp=0
  for(i in 1:length(n)){
    exp=exp+n[i]/sum(n)*percent[i]
  }
  return(exp)
}
expected=NULL
actual=NULL
for(i in 1:length(unique(NBA_data$name))){
  temp=NBA_data %>% filter(name==unique(NBA_data$name)[i]) %>% group_by(action_type) %>% summarize(n=n(),percent=sum(shot_made_flag)/n)
  expected[i]=expected_percent(NBA_selection$percent,temp$n)
  actual[i]=expected_percent(temp$percent,temp$n)
}
ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x=actual,y=expected))+
  ylim(0,1)

Summary

Most of our questions concerned how the type of shots teams took correlated with a team’s efficiency. The questions concerning efficiency and how a shot’s chances of going in over the course of game lead to our follow up questions. We were surprised that 3 pointers were less than 10% of all shots as shown by our table in the initial questions. Regarding a shot’s preference and its efficiency, when the shots were classified into four groups based on their types, there was a moderately strong, positive relationship between the shots that players prefer and their efficiencies. We initially expected that the most efficient action types in an offense would be dunks and layup shots based on the graph on action type and efficiency. However, we were surprised to see that jumpshots and dunks have a similar expected efficiency in an NBA offense, and the expected efficiency of layups was much higher than other types of shots. Such correlation has led us to investigate more in depth on how the quantity of shots influences a team’s net efficiency.

Our initial follow up question was to explore how a team’s shot selection on offense, and the kinds of shots they allow on defense, affected their net rating. I ran stepwise regression on my predictors to obtain coefficients on test data, and then I used the model on the test dataset for cross validation purposes. Our model did not perform great as the figure and cross validation correlation shows. I think we will explore combining the shot types into smaller groups, and creating new factor variables that have levels such as “driving”, “floating”, “cutting”, that indicate if the shot was off of a drive, cut, etc. I also wanted to see if certain shot percentages varied over the course of the game but there was almost no evidence from the chi sq test.
